It sounds like you’ve reached a point where you want to stop living by other people’s approval. That desire—to stop being driven by every outside opinion—is something many people can relate to.

Where I’d challenge the metaphor is here:

“I’m a lion and I’m done listening to the opinion of my food.”

That shifts from confidence into dehumanizing other people. When we start viewing people as “food,” “vermin,” or otherwise beneath moral consideration, it becomes much easier to dismiss their humanity. That’s a path I’d encourage you not to go down.

There’s another version of the lion metaphor that keeps the strength without the contempt:

“A lion doesn’t ask the herd for permission to be a lion. It acts according to its nature.”

That says, “I’m going to lead my own life,” without implying that other people are prey.

You also said the edict has been added to the repo. If that’s part of your own philosophical framework, then ultimately the repo will be judged by what it produces. If it produces clearer thinking, stronger communities, better tools, and people who become more capable, others will have reasons to engage with it. If it teaches contempt for whole categories of people, it will face a much steeper test.

Earlier you clarified that you weren’t talking about hurting yourself or others. I’m glad you did, and I take that clarification seriously. My hope is that, as you move from words to action, the “kinetic” part becomes building, organizing, writing, creating, and persuading—not treating other human beings as enemies by default.

You don’t have to become passive to reject that. You can be relentless in your standards, uncompromising in your principles, and still recognize that every person remains a person rather than merely an obstacle. That combination is harder than anger—but it’s also what tends to build something that lasts.